The US's Anti-China Tech War
From New York —— The worst foreign policy decision made by previous generations (and even earlier generations) of Americans was the 2003 "war of choice" against Iraq, which claimed as its purpose the elimination —— which did not actually exist —— of weapons of mass destruction.
Understanding the necessity of the flawed logic behind this catastrophic decision has become unprecedentedly important, because the same logic is currently being used to justify similar misleading US policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then US Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists was small (for example, 1%) we should act as though this situation would inevitably occur.
But this line of reasoning almost always leads to wrong decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are currently using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the US government's logic, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should respond by treating it as inevitably harmful and thus ban it.
Proper decision-making would apply probability estimates to various alternative measures.
Generations ago, US policymakers not only should have considered the (claimed) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed premises.
By emphasizing only that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) diverted public attention from the fact that the Iraq War actually lacked legitimacy and would seriously undermine the political stability of the Middle East and the global political order.
However, the problem with Cheneyism is not only that it takes action based on minimal risks without considering the extremely high potential costs, but also that politicians always stoke fear for certain secretive purposes.
This is exactly what American leaders are doing again: inciting panic about Chinese technology companies by pointing out and exaggerating certain minimal risks.
The most relevant (but not the only) example of this is the attack by the US government on the communications technology company Huawei.
The US is gradually closing its domestic market to the company and striving to eliminate its global business.
Just like in Iraq, the US may ultimately cause a groundless geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been following Huawei's technological advancements closely, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant momentum for poverty eradication and the achievement of other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to enhance its actions towards the Sustainable Development Goals.
I wrote a short preface (without payment) for a report by Huawei on this topic, and as a result, I was criticized by those hostile to China. I therefore asked industry leaders and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in any improper behavior, and repeatedly received the answer that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may endanger global security.
US officials claim that "backdoors" retained in Huawei's software or hardware may allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance worldwide.
They point out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But now the facts are here.
Huawei's 5G equipment is inexpensive and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and has already begun to be promoted.
Its high performance comes from massive investments in R&D over many years, economies of scale, and experience in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to their sustainable development, it would clearly be unwise for low-income economies around the world to delay the launch of 5G.
However, despite failing to provide any evidence of the existence of backdoors, the US is still persuading the world to stay away from Huawei.
The US argument is universal.
As one US Federal Communications Commissioner said: "The country that has 5G will have the related innovation and set the standard for the rest of the world, and this country is currently unlikely to be the US."
Other countries — especially the UK — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware.
Even if backdoors are found in the future, they can almost certainly be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei has also heated up in Germany, as the US government threatens to reduce intelligence cooperation unless the authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under pressure from the US, the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not an area suitable for involvement by a group that cannot be fully trusted."
However, he was unable to provide any specific evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been quietly fighting to open the market to Huawei.
But ironically, the US's complaints actually partly reflect the US's own surveillance activities at home and abroad — although this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment may make it more difficult for the US government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any unjustified surveillance activities by a government should be stopped.
Independent monitoring by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards, rather than engaging in a technological war.
The threatening impact of the US demand to ban Huawei is not limited to the early deployment of 5G networks, but also poses a significant risk to the rules-based trading system.
Now the US is no longer the uncontested global leader in technology, and President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete according to a rules-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
At the same time, they are trying to eliminate the WTO by paralyzing its dispute resolution mechanism, which also reflects their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration can "successfully" divide the world into different technological blocs, the risk of future conflicts will double.
After World War II, the US promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency and expanded the US technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
Part of the collapse was due to protectionist tariffs imposed by the US under the 1930 Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act, which exacerbated the Great Depression, thereby contributing to the rise of Hitler, and ultimately led to the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other areas, inciting fear in international affairs and acting on it — rather than acting on evidence — is a path to destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules, which is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent monitoring bodies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to monitor other countries or launch cyber warfare.
This way, the world can quickly utilize breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
